Preheat your oven to 200°C. Peel and chop the @potato{450%g} into 2cm chunks.

Peel and chop the @eschalion shallot{1}(halved and chopped into small pieces). Cut the @ginger{1%piece} in half. Peel and grate one half of the ginger.

Peel and finely slice the @garlic clove{1}(finely sliced).

Halve the @plum{2}(halved and stones removed) and cut into 2cm wedges.

Slice the @pak choi{1}(quartered lengthways).

Put a large #saucepan{} of water with a pinch of @salt{pinch} on to boil for the potato.

Pop the bok choy, garlic and unpeeled ginger onto a large piece of #foil{} (or #parchment{}) and pop onto a #tray{}. Add 2 tbsp of @water{2%tbsp} and a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @black pepper{pinch}. Scrunch the foil together to enclose.

Heat a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. While the pan gets hot, pop the @duck breast{2} on a #chopping board{}, skin-side up. Use a sharp #knife{} to score the skin of the duck into a criss-cross pattern (don't cut through to the flesh!). Season both sides of the duck with @salt{} and @black pepper{}.

Meanwhile, lay the duck skin-side down in the hot pan. Sprinkle the @Chinese five spice{1/2%tsp} evenly over the flesh side of the duck (only use a little bit!).

> IMPORTANT: Remember to wash your hands after handling raw meat.

Cook until the skin is crisp, ~{5%minutes}. Turn, cook for ~{1%minute} on the flesh side to seal the meat. Remove to a #baking tray{} skin-side up and roast on the top shelf of your oven until cooked, ~{15%minutes}. Once cooked, remove from your oven and rest in a warm place, (wrapped in #tin foil{} if you have some) for ~{10%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The duck is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle. Keep the pan!

Meanwhile, add the potato to the boiling water and cook until tender, ~{15-20%minutes}.

> Tip: The potatoes are done when you can easily slip a knife through the middle!

When the potatoes are done, drain in a #colander{} and return to the pan (off the heat). Add the @unsalted butter{30%g} and season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Mash with a #potato masher{} until smooth. Cover with a #lid{} to keep warm.

Return the frying pan to a medium heat (you'll use the duck fat in the pan instead of oil). Once hot, add the shallot and cook until softened, ~{3%minutes}. Stir in the plums, ginger and @sugar{2%tsp}. Cook for ~{1%minute} more then add the @soy sauce{25%ml}.

Increase the heat, bring to the boil then add the @red wine stock paste{14%g} and @water for the sauce{150%ml}. Stir to dissolve the stock. Reduce the heat and leave to simmer until thickened and glossy, ~{6-8%minutes}. Meanwhile, pop the bok choy parcel in the oven. Bake until tender, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Once everything is ready, cut each duck breast into five or six thin slices and stir any resting juices into the plum sauce. Divide the mash between your #plates{} and place the sliced duck on top. Spoon the plum sauce all over and serve the steamed bok choy on the side (discard the garlic and ginger!). Enjoy - Happy Chinese New Year!